y of the nation state, and especially its relationship to ethnic minorities, such as the Slovaks. Confrontational nationalism and the use of ethnicity as a political tool are no less common today than they were in the 20th century. This book’s radical contribution to studies of nationalism and ethnicity is that it juxtaposes German and Czech perspectives of power and oppression as part of the same story. This framework allows us to appreciate new complexities regarding the creation of Czechoslovakia and ponder them in 21st century terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 4aDeutschland. 4aEthnizität. 4aNationalsozialismus. 4aTschechoslowakei. 4aÖsterreichisch-Ungarisches Reich. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aAustro-Hungarian empire.  aCzechs.  aEthnicity.  aGermans.  aNationalism.  aSlovaks.1 aAlexander, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarshall Thomas, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarshall Thomas, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPistalo, Vladimir, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cEPUBz97831107499530 cprintz978311074940340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110749885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110749885/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK